<Base title="The Only 6 SaaS Metrics Indie Founders Actually Need to Track" description="Skip the vanity metrics. Here are the 6 SaaS numbers that actually tell you if your business is healthy — and how to track them without expensive tools.">
  <article class="blog-post">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="post-header">
        <time datetime="2026-04-07">April 7, 2026</time>
        <h1>The Only 6 SaaS Metrics Indie Founders Actually Need to Track</h1>
        <p class="post-lead">
          You don't need a 50-metric dashboard when you have 30 customers. Here are the six numbers that actually matter at the early stage.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          Let me save you some time. I spent weeks reading every "SaaS metrics guide" on the internet, and most of them are written for Series B startups with data teams. If you're an indie founder with a Stripe account and a dream, you need a much shorter list.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here are the six metrics I actually check every week. No fluff, no "north star metric" philosophy essays. Just numbers.
        </p>

        <h2>1. MRR (Monthly Recurring Revenue)</h2>
        <p>
          This is the number. If you track nothing else, track this. MRR tells you how much predictable revenue you're generating each month from subscriptions.
        </p>
        <p>
          The formula is straightforward: add up all your active subscription revenue on a monthly basis. Annual subscriptions get divided by 12. Simple.
        </p>
        <p>
          What trips people up is <strong>changes in MRR</strong>. You want to break it down into: new MRR (new customers), expansion MRR (upgrades), contraction MRR (downgrades), and churned MRR (cancellations). This tells you where your growth is actually coming from.
        </p>

        <h2>2. ARR (Annual Recurring Revenue)</h2>
        <p>
          ARR = MRR x 12. It's that simple. Some founders think ARR is only for companies with annual plans — nope. It's just a way to contextualize your revenue at a yearly scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          I find ARR more useful for goal-setting. "I want to hit $50K ARR" sounds more concrete than "$4,166 MRR." Same number, different psychology.
        </p>

        <h2>3. Churn Rate</h2>
        <p>
          Churn rate = (customers lost during a period / customers at the start of that period) x 100.
        </p>
        <p>
          For indie SaaS, anything under 5% monthly churn is decent. Under 3% is good. Under 1% means you're doing something really right (or you have annual contracts).
        </p>
        <p>
          The thing about churn is that it compounds brutally. At 5% monthly churn, you lose half your customers in about 13 months. At 10%, you lose half in 7 months. These are the kinds of numbers that look fine month-to-month but will quietly kill your business.
        </p>

        <h2>4. LTV (Lifetime Value)</h2>
        <p>
          LTV tells you how much revenue a customer generates before they churn. The simple formula: ARPU / monthly churn rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Why does this matter? Because it sets the ceiling for your customer acquisition cost (CAC). If your LTV is $200, you shouldn't be spending $250 to acquire a customer. Seems obvious, but you'd be surprised how many founders have no idea what their LTV is.
        </p>

        <h2>5. ARPU (Average Revenue Per User)</h2>
        <p>
          ARPU = MRR / total active customers. This tells you if you have a pricing problem.
        </p>
        <p>
          If your ARPU is $5 and your support costs are $3 per customer, you're in trouble. If your ARPU is $50, you have room to breathe.
        </p>
        <p>
          Watching ARPU over time also tells you if your pricing changes are working. Launched a higher tier? ARPU should go up. If it doesn't, nobody's buying it.
        </p>

        <h2>6. Revenue Breakdown</h2>
        <p>
          This isn't one metric — it's a view. You want to see your revenue broken down by: new, expansion, contraction, and churned. Ideally visualized over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          A revenue breakdown chart is worth more than any single number because it tells you the <em>story</em>. Are you growing because of new customers or because existing customers are upgrading? Are you losing revenue from churn or from downgrades? The answer changes your strategy completely.
        </p>

        <h2>OK great, but how do I actually track these?</h2>
        <p>
          If you're using Stripe (and most indie founders are), you have three options:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Spreadsheets.</strong> Export your Stripe data, write formulas, and update it manually. Works at first. Gets painful fast.</li>
          <li><strong>Enterprise analytics tools.</strong> Baremetrics, ChartMogul, ProfitWell. Powerful, but expensive. $50-200+/month is steep when you're at $500 MRR.</li>
          <li><strong>Lightweight tools built for indie scale.</strong> This is why I built <a href="/tools/mrrscope">MRRScope</a> — it connects to Stripe, calculates all six of these metrics automatically, and costs $29 one-time. You can even try it with demo data before connecting anything.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          Whatever you choose, just start tracking. The founders who know their numbers make better decisions than the ones who don't. It's that simple.
        </p>

